fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
With the substitution rule, we need two more congruence rules to
    convert judgmental equality of terms and types.
             \frac {             \Gamma \vdash  a\equiv  a':A             \quad              \Gamma ,x:A,\Delta \vdash  B \space \text {type}         }{             \Gamma ,\Delta [x:=a]\vdash  B[x:=a]\equiv  B[x:=a'] \space \text {type}         }     

             \frac {             \Gamma \vdash  A\equiv  A'\space \text {type}             \quad              \Gamma ,x:A,\Delta \vdash  b:A         }{             \Gamma ,\Delta [x:=a]\vdash  b[x:=a]\equiv  b[x:=a']:A'[x:=a] \space \text {type}         }

In type theory, natural number is defined using peano encoding.
    The type \mathbb {N} is formed by the formation rule:
             \frac {}{\vdash \mathbb {N}\space \text {type}}\mathbb {N}\text {-form}

Peano's first axiom postulates the existence of a natural number 0.
    The introduction rule for \mathbb {N} has a 0 constructor and a successor function.
             \frac {}{\vdash 0:\mathbb {N}}\mathbb {N}\text {-intro-0}         \quad          \frac {}{\vdash \text {succ}:\mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}} \mathbb {N}\text {-intro-succ}

Recall the definition of addition function \text {add}: \mathbb {N}\to (\mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}) satisfying the specification:
             \begin {align*}             m + 0 & :\equiv  m             \\              m + \text {succ}(n) & :\equiv  \text {succ}(m + n)         \end {align*}     
    Such definition is enough to characterize the addition function.
    Because it postulates te behavior of \text {add}_\mathbb {N} at the constructor of \mathbb {N}

More generally, we can define a dependent function f:\Pi  n:\mathbb {N}.P(n) by induction on n using
             \begin {align*}             p_0 & : P(0)             \\             p_S & : \Pi _{(n:\mathbb {N})}P(n)\to  P(\text {succ}(n))         \end {align*}     
    Just present the definition by writing
             \begin {align*}             f(0) & :\equiv  p_0             \\             f(\text {succ}(n)) & :\equiv  p_S(n,f(n))         \end {align*}     
    f is said to be defined by pattern matching on the variable n.

The Fibonacci function is a well-known function in mathematics.
    It is defined by pattern matching on the variable n as follows:
             \begin {align*}             \text {fib}(0) & :\equiv  0             \\             \text {fib}(1) & :\equiv  1             \\             \text {fib}(n+2) & :\equiv  \text {fib}(n) + \text {fib}(n+1)         \end {align*}

Let A and B be types. The coproduct (disjoint sum) A+B is a typed defined by the following constructors:
\text {inl}:A\to A+B
\text {inr}:B\to A+B For any type family indexed by x:A+B, satisfies the following induction principle: \text {ind}_+: (\Pi _{(x:A)}P(\text {inl}(x)))\to (\Pi _{(y:B)}P(\text {inr}(y)))\to \Pi _{(z:A+B)}P(z) (Note that sometimes we denoted \text {ind}_+(f,g) as [f,g]) And the computation rule: \begin {align*} \text {ind}_+(f,g,\text {inl}(x))&\equiv f(x)\\ \text {ind}_+(f,g,\text {inr}(y))&\equiv g(y) \end {align*} where f and g are defined: \begin {align*} f&:\Pi _{(x:A)}P(\text {inl}(x))\\ g&:\Pi _{(y:B)}P(\text {inr}(y)) \end {align*} This can be presented by pattern matching to define a function h:\Pi _{(z:A+B)}.P(z): \begin {align*} h(\text {inl}(x))&:\equiv f(x)\\ h(\text {inr}(y))&:\equiv g(y) \end {align*}

Consider a type A and let a:A be an element.
    The identity type of A at a is an inductive family of types a=_Ax 
    indexed by x:A.
             \frac {             \Gamma \vdash  a:A         }{             \Gamma ,x:A\vdash  a=_Ax\space \text {type}         }     
    The only constructor is the refl:
             \frac {             \Gamma \vdash  a:A         }{             \Gamma \vdash  \text {refl}_a:a=_Ax         }

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
The induction principle of the identity type states that
for any type family P(x,p) indexed by x:A and p:a=_Ax,
         \text {ind-eq}_{a}:P(a, \text {refl}_a)\to  (x:A)\to  (p:a=_Ax)\to  P(x,p)     
satisfies \text {ind-eq}_{a}(u,a,\text {refl}_a)\equiv  u where u:P(a,\text {refl}_a).
Formally we can write:
         \frac {             \Gamma \vdash  a:A,\quad  \Gamma ,x:A,p:a=_Ax\vdash  P(x,p)\space \text {type}         }{             \Gamma \vdash  \text {ind-eq}_{a}(a,\text {refl}_a): P(a,\text {refl}_a) \to  (x:A)\to  (p:a=_Ax)\to  P(x,p)         }\text {eq-elim}     
         \frac {             \Gamma \vdash  a:A,\quad  \Gamma ,x:A,p:a=_Ax\vdash  P(x,p)\space \text {type}         }{             \Gamma ,u:P(a,\text {refl}_a)\vdash  \text {ind-eq}_{a}(u,a,\text {refl}_a)\equiv  u:P(a,\text {refl}_a)         }\text {eq-comp}

We can form an identity type with variables of A.
         \Gamma ,x:A,y:A\vdash  x=_Ay\space \text {type}     
with the following introduction rule:
         \frac {             \Gamma ,x:A\vdash  x:A         }{             \Gamma ,x:A\vdash  \text {refl}_x:x=_Ax         }     
and similarly the elimination rule and computation rule.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let A be a type.
    We defined the unit law operations for x=_Ay:
             \begin {align*}             \text {left-unit} & : (x=_Ay)\to  (\text {refl}_x\cdot  x = x) \\             \text {right-unit} & : (x=_Ay)\to  (x\cdot \text {refl}_y = x)         \end {align*}

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
By elimination it suffices to construct:
         \begin {align*}             \text {left-unit}(\text {refl}_x) &: \text {refl}_x \cdot  \text {refl}_x = \text {refl}_x \\             \text {right-unit}(\text {refl}_x) &: \text {refl}_x \cdot  \text {refl}_x = \text {refl}_x         \end {align*}     
In both cases we need only to construct \text {refl}_{\text {refl}_x}.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let f:A\to B be a map. We define the action on paths of f as an operation: \text {ap}_f : \prod _{x,y:A} (x=y) \to (f(x)=f(y)) This can be defined by induction principle of identity types: \text {ap}_f(\text {refl}_x) \equiv \text {refl}_{f(x)} And there are operations: \text {ap-id}_A: \prod _{(x,y:A)}\prod _{(p:x=y)} p = \text {ap}_{\text {id}_A}(p) Taking \text {ap-id}_A(\text {refl}_x) \equiv \text {refl}_{\text {refl}_x} Finally we can construct \text {ap-comp}(f, g): \prod _{(x,y:A)}\prod _{(p:x=y)} \text {ap}_{f\circ g}(p) = \text {ap}_f(\text {ap}_g(p)) by taking \text {ap-comp}(f,g,\text {refl}_x) \equiv \text {refl}_{\text {refl}_{g(f(x))}} There are identifications:
Notice that we have \text {ap-id}_A(\text {refl}_x) \equiv \text {refl}_{\text {refl}_x} so \begin {align*} \text {ap-refl}(f,x) &:\text {ap}_f(\text {refl}_x) = \text {refl}_{f(x)} \\ \text {ap-refl}(f,x) &\equiv \text {refl}_{\text {refl}_{f(x)}} \end {align*}
The \text {ap-inv} can be constructed by identification elimination on p. \begin {align*} &\text {ap-inv}(f,p):\text {ap}_f(p^{-1}) = \text {ap}_f(p)^{-1}\\ &\text {ap-inv}(f,\text {refl}_x)\equiv \text {refl}_{\text {ap}_f(\text {refl}_x)} \end {align*}
Similarly, the \text {ap-concat} can be constructed by identification elimination on p. \begin {align*} &\text {ap-concat}(f,p,q):\text {ap}_f(p\cdot q) = \text {ap}_f(p)\cdot \text {ap}_f(q) \\ &\text {ap-concat}(f,\text {refl}_x,q)\equiv \text {refl}_{\text {ap}_f(q)} \end {align*}

We assume that there're enough universe, i.e.,
    for every finite list of types in context 
             \Gamma _1\vdash  A_1\space \space \text {type},\cdots ,\Gamma _n\vdash  A_n\space \space \text {type}     
    there is a universe \mathcal {U} that contains each A_i in the sense that \mathcal {U} comes equipped with
             \Gamma _i\vdash \check {A_i}:\mathcal {U}     
    for which the following judgement holds:
             \Gamma _i \vdash \mathcal {T}(\check {A_i})\equiv  A_i\space \space \text {type}

The successor universee \mathcal {U}^+ of a universe \mathcal {U} is defined using universe postulate
    with the following contexts:
             \vdash \mathcal {U}\space \space \text {type}\quad  X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \mathcal {T}(X)\space \space \text {type}     
    It therefore contains the type \mathcal {U} as well as type in \mathcal {U}, in the following sense
             \begin {align*}             &\vdash \check {\mathcal {U}}:\mathcal {U}^+\\              &\vdash \mathcal {T}^+(\check {\mathcal {U}})\equiv \mathcal {U}\space \text {type}\\             &X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \check {\mathcal {T}}(X):\mathcal {U}^+\\              &X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \mathcal {T}^+(\check {\mathcal {T}}(X))\equiv \mathcal {T}(X)\space \text {type}          \end {align*}

Now let's try to construct some graphs using the Relation type and the Num instance:

  ghci> 1 * (2 + 3) :: Relation Int
R {domain = fromList [1,2,3], relation = fromList [(1,2),(1,3)]}
ghci> 1 * 2 * 3 :: Relation Int
R {domain = fromList [1,2,3], relation = fromList [(1,2),(1,3),(2,3)]}

We define a map \text {Sub}:

Basis: \forall  x\in  V,\text {Sub}(x) =\{ x \}

Application: \forall  M,N\in \Lambda ,\text {Sub}(MN) = \text {Sub}(M)\cup \text {Sub}(N)\cup \{ MN \}

Abstraction: \forall  x\in  V,M\in \Lambda ,\text {Sub}(\lambda  x.M) = \text {Sub}(M)\cup \{ \lambda  x.M \}
    L is a subterm of M if L\in \text {Sub}(M).
    If L\not \equiv  M then we say L is a proper subterm of M.

Let FV(L) be the set of free variables in a term L.

Variable: \forall  x\in  V,\text {FV}(x) = \{ x \}

Application: \forall  M,N\in \Lambda ,\text {FV}(MN) = \text {FV}(M)\cup \text {FV}(N)

Abstraction: \forall  x\in  V,M\in \Lambda ,\text {FV}(\lambda  x.M) = \text {FV}(M)\setminus \{ x \}

Let X and Y be sets.
    For any set A and function
    f: A \to  X and g: A \to  Y,
    there exists a unique function h: A \to  X \times  Y such that
    the following diagram commutes:





